<h1>Closures are simple</h1>

<p>You probably shouldn't tell a six-year old about closures, but if you do, you might say that closure gives an ability to gain access to a variable declared in some other function scope.</p>

<p><a href="https://i.stack.imgur.com/OX92v.png" rel="noreferrer"><img src="https://i.stack.imgur.com/OX92v.png" alt="enter image description here"></a></p>

<p><div class="snippet" data-lang="js" data-hide="false" data-console="false" data-babel="false">
<div class="snippet-code">
<pre class="snippet-code-js lang-js prettyprint-override"><code>function getA() {
  var a = [];

  // this action happens later,
  // after the function returned
  // the `a` value
  setTimeout(function() {
    a.splice(0, 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5);
  });

  return a;
}

var a = getA();
out('What is `a` length?');
out('`a` length is ' + a.length);

setTimeout(function() {
  out('No wait...');
  out('`a` length is ' + a.length);
  out('OK :|')
});</code></pre>
<pre class="snippet-code-html lang-html prettyprint-override"><code>&lt;pre id="output"&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  function out(k) {
    document.getElementById('output').innerHTML += '&gt; ' + k + '\n';
  }
&lt;/script&gt;</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
</p>
